<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Merlot's aging potential varies dramatically based on quality and origin. <strong>Premium Bordeaux Right Bank wines</strong> like Pétrus and Le Pin can cellar magnificently for 20-30 years, while top Washington State and Napa Valley Merlots peak at 10-15 years. Entry-level Merlot is best consumed within 3-5 years to preserve its approachable fruit character.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Most Merlots show beautifully in their <strong>youth (2-5 years)</strong> when primary fruit flavors shine. Premium bottlings enter their optimal drinking window around year 7-10, when secondary complexity emerges. The finest examples develop tertiary notes—leather, tobacco, and earthy minerality—after a decade in proper storage.</p>

<h3>Evolution in the Bottle</h3>
<p>Merlot's transformation is particularly graceful. Initially firm tannins soften and integrate, while bright cherry and plum flavors evolve into <strong>dried fruit, fig, and prune characteristics</strong>. The wine's natural tendency toward lower acidity means it develops a silky, almost creamy texture with age. Color shifts from deep purple to brick-red edges, and aromatic complexity increases as vanilla oak notes meld with developing tertiary bouquet.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store Merlot at a consistent <strong>55-60°F (13-15°C)</strong> with 60-70% humidity. Keep bottles on their side to maintain cork moisture, away from light and vibration. Temperature fluctuations are more damaging than slightly warmer storage.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Properly aged Merlot shows <strong>integrated tannins, developed aromatics, and harmonious balance</strong>. Warning signs include excessive browning (especially in wines under 8 years old), vinegar aromas indicating acetobacter, or mushroom/wet cardboard notes suggesting cork taint. A slight sediment deposit is normal in aged Merlot and indicates proper development rather than deterioration.</p>

